{
  "texts": [
    "The pros of this approach are its low training cost and the fact that the LLM parameters remain unchanged, often yielding better results than simple prompt engineering.",
    "The cons include the limited ability to improve performance without altering all model parameters and a slight inference slowdown. 4.",
    "Fine-Tuning and Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning: Looking beyond closedsource LLMs, the availability of open-source LLMs with accessible model weights, such as those in the LLaMA [49,[57][58][59], Mistral [60], Gemma [61,62], and Phi [63] families, opens fine-tuning opportunities.",
    "Fine-tuning involves starting from pretrained LLM weights and continuing training (changing the model weights) using domain-specific data.",
    "As demonstrated by various studies, fine-tuning works really well for customizing LLMs for domain problems."
  ]
}